{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8c34fe1-c16b-44c7-b212-aa96970ea29f","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is passed to the new test platform runner.\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n| Old (VSTest) | New package |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nAlso ensure your test project sets `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` (or `<UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>`) in the `.csproj` so `dotnet test` routes through the new platform instead of VSTest.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4812fa4-0864-4ef3-89ea-5245bb49f245","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `dotnet test` still works but the underlying runner changes\n- Filter syntax changes from `--filter` to `--filter` (similar but may need adjustment)\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage or you use a different mechanism\n\n\n- Blame options like `--blame-crash` and `--blame-hang` also shift with the new platform\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can run the test executable directly or continue using `dotnet test` as a compatibility layer, though the CLI options change significantly. The filter syntax generally stays the same, but you'll need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package for TRX reporting, and code coverage collection uses different mechanisms depending on your setup.\n\nThe crash and hang dump options get renamed to `--crashdump` and `--hangdump` respectively, with corresponding timeout parameters, and each requires its own extension package. When using `dotnet test`, some of these options pass through with a `--` separator. There are really two execution paths here: running the test executable directly with options, or going through `dotnet test` which acts as a compatibility layer. Alternatively, you can run the test executable directly with those same options. I should also mention the required NuGet packages for each extension—the TRX report generator, code coverage collector, crash dump, and hang dump handlers—and note that the cobertura format requires the Microsoft.CodeCoverage package to work properly with the new testing platform.","outputTokens":1239,"requestId":"BD01:39A6CA:1D2BDE0:20DD7E1:6A07C515"},"id":"5feeb93d-fedd-495a-a2e1-fa496469dad6","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:15:22.426Z","parentId":"fc704e9e-5b1c-44ca-ad4e-0e21d01c85d5"}
